ommunities in the face of white resistance that cast them as perpetual aliens. Amezcua charts the diverse strategies used by Mexican Chicagoans to fight the forces of segregation, economic predation, and gentrification, focusing on how unlikely combinations of social conservatism and the real estate market savvy paved new paths for Latinx assimilation. Making Mexican Chicago offers a powerful multiracial history of Chicago that sheds new light on the origins and endurance of urban inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMexican American neighborhoodszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican AmericansxHousingzIllinoiszChicago. 0aMexican AmericanszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexicanszIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aSegregationzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban renewalzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aLatino politics, spatial segregation, racial capitalism, Mexican immigration, Mexican Americans, white flight, real estate, urbanism, gentrification, political economy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226815831423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226815831/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles